page.title: 16Wildlife
page.content: There is a small lake in Grizedale called Grizedale Tarn. It is about 60 feet deep in the middle and turns round anti_clockwise very slowly. When you drop a matchstick in the tarn it takes three and a quarter hours before the matchstick gets back to its original place if there is no wind. The tarn never loses its water level because there is a spring under it. People have seen the{holly blue {butterfly}frequently in this area. {Lizards}and{woodpeckers}(green and pied) live in the woods. The{sundew} plant and the{sloworm}can be seen occasionally. On its sticky stalks the sundew plant catches flies which come down to drink the juice. Many kinds of fungi can be found in the autumn including the{fly agaric,} the{chanterelle}and several types of {boletus}and{russula.
